var tafsirData_21 = {
  1: {
    "˹The time of˺ people's judgment has drawn near": "The Day of Judgment, when every person will be held accountable for their deeds, is approaching fast. In the sight of Allah, its arrival is certain and imminent, even if humans perceive it as distant. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) said, 'I and the Hour have been sent like these two,' and he joined his index and middle fingers together, showing how close the end times are to his mission. This is a wake-up call that life is short and accountability is real.",
    "yet they are heedlessly turning away": "Despite this reality, people remain in a state of neglect and distraction. They are so absorbed in worldly pursuits—wealth, entertainment, status—that they ignore the warnings about the Hereafter. It is like a student who knows an important exam is coming but keeps procrastinating, never preparing until it is too late. This heedlessness is not due to lack of knowledge but a deliberate turning away from the truth."
  },
  2: {
    "Whatever new reminder comes to them from their Lord": "Whenever a fresh portion of the Quran was revealed, containing guidance, wisdom, and warnings, it was meant to awaken their hearts and bring them closer to Allah. Allah, out of His mercy, continuously sent reminders through His Messenger to guide humanity. These revelations addressed their current situations and answered their doubts.",
    "they only listen to it jokingly": "Instead of taking these divine words seriously, they treated them as entertainment or a joke. They would listen but with mockery in their hearts, not with the intention to learn or reflect. This attitude reflects spiritual arrogance—when a person thinks they are too smart or too important to humble themselves before God's guidance. It is like someone receiving life-saving medical advice but laughing it off instead of following it."
  },
  3: {
    "with their hearts ˹totally˺ distracted": "Their hearts were not present when listening to the Quran. They were preoccupied with worldly desires, entertainment, and trivial matters. A distracted heart cannot benefit from guidance, just as a cup already full of dirty water cannot receive clean water. True listening requires an attentive and humble heart.",
    "The evildoers would converse secretly": "The leaders among the disbelievers would hold private meetings to plot against the Prophet and conspire how to turn people away from his message. They did this secretly because they knew their arguments were weak and could not withstand public scrutiny. This shows that rejection of truth often involves deliberate scheming rather than honest disagreement.",
    "˹saying,˺ \"Is this ˹one˺ not human like yourselves?": "Their main objection was that Muhammad (peace be upon him) was a human being, not an angel or a supernatural being. They expected a messenger to be something extraordinary in appearance or nature. This reveals their misunderstanding of prophethood—Allah sends human messengers so people can relate to them, learn from them, and follow their example. If an angel were sent, people would say, 'We cannot follow him; he does not understand human struggles.'",
    "Would you fall for ˹this˺ witchcraft, even though you can ˹clearly˺ see?\"": "They accused the Prophet of being a magician and the Quran of being magic that deceives people. This accusation was baseless because magic involves trickery and illusions, while the Quran calls to truth, justice, and worship of One God. They could 'clearly see' that Muhammad was known among them as Al-Amin (the Trustworthy) before prophethood, yet they chose to ignore his noble character and honest reputation."
  },
  4: {
    "The Prophet responded, \"My Lord ˹fully˺ knows every word spoken in the heavens and the earth": "The Prophet did not argue or become defensive. Instead, he reminded them that Allah is fully aware of everything—their secret plots, their whispered conversations, and their public accusations. Nothing is hidden from Allah, whether in the heavens or on earth. This response shows the Prophet's trust in Allah and his confidence that the truth will prevail.",
    "For He is the All-Hearing, All-Knowing\"": "Allah hears every sound and knows every thought. This is a warning to those who plot in secret, thinking no one knows. It is also a comfort to the believers that Allah is aware of the injustice they face and will bring justice in His perfect timing. The Prophet essentially said: 'You may whisper your plots, but my Lord hears everything, and He will hold you accountable.'"
  },
  5: {
    "Yet they say, \"This ˹Quran˺ is a set of confused dreams!": "They claimed the Quran was nothing but a collection of mixed-up, meaningless dreams that Muhammad experienced. This accusation was absurd because the Quran is perfectly structured, logically coherent, and contains profound wisdom that no dream could produce. Dreams are personal and often confusing, but the Quran addresses all of humanity with clear guidance.",
    "No, he has fabricated it!": "When the dream theory did not stick, they changed their accusation, saying Muhammad made it up himself. But how could an unlettered man who never studied poetry or rhetoric produce a book that the greatest Arab poets could not match? The Quran itself challenged them to produce even one chapter like it, and they failed.",
    "No, he must be a poet!": "They then called him a poet, suggesting the Quran was simply beautiful poetry. But Arabic poetry follows specific meters and patterns, and the Quran does not conform to any of them. Moreover, poets often spoke of love, wine, and tribal pride, while the Quran speaks of monotheism, morality, and the afterlife. Their contradictory accusations show their confusion and desperation.",
    "So let him bring us a ˹tangible˺ sign like those ˹prophets˺ sent before\"": "Finally, they demanded miracles like those given to previous prophets—splitting the sea like Moses or raising the dead like Jesus. But they were not sincere in this demand. Allah knew that even if such signs were shown, they would not believe. The Quran itself is the greatest miracle—a living, preserved sign that continues to guide humanity."
  },
  6: {
    "Not a ˹single˺ society We destroyed before them ever believed ˹after receiving the signs˺": "Allah reminds them of a historical pattern: previous nations that demanded miraculous signs and then rejected them were destroyed. The people of Thamud demanded a she-camel as a sign, and when it was given, they killed it and were destroyed. The people of Pharaoh saw numerous signs through Moses but still disbelieved and drowned. Miracles do not guarantee faith; a sincere heart does.",
    "Will these ˹pagans˺ then believe?": "This is a rhetorical question implying that if previous nations with their demanded miracles did not believe, what guarantee is there that the Meccan pagans would believe? Their problem was not lack of evidence but arrogance and unwillingness to submit to the truth. This verse serves as a warning that demanding signs while having an insincere heart leads to destruction, not guidance."
  },
  7: {
    "We did not send ˹messengers˺ before you ˹O Prophet˺ except mere men inspired by Us": "Allah clarifies that every messenger before Muhammad—Noah, Abraham, Moses, Jesus, and all others—were human beings, not angels. They ate food, walked in marketplaces, had families, and experienced human emotions. This was Allah's consistent method because human messengers can relate to human struggles, serve as practical role models, and demonstrate that following divine guidance is achievable for ordinary people.",
    "If you ˹polytheists˺ do not know ˹this already˺, then ask those who have knowledge ˹of the Scriptures˺": "If the Meccan pagans doubted this, they were invited to verify with the Jews and Christians who possessed previous scriptures. The Torah and the Gospel confirmed that Moses, David, and Jesus were all human prophets. This invitation to research shows that Islam encourages seeking knowledge and verifying claims rather than blind following."
  },
  8: {
    "We did not give those messengers ˹supernatural˺ bodies that did not need food": "The prophets were not given bodies that transcended human needs. They felt hunger and ate, they felt thirst and drank, they experienced fatigue and rested. This is important because it shows that spiritual excellence does not require abandoning human nature. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) fasted, but he also enjoyed good food. He prayed at night, but he also slept. Balance is key in Islam.",
    "nor were they immortal": "Every prophet, no matter how great, eventually died. This is a reminder that immortality belongs only to Allah. The death of prophets also tests their followers—will they continue on the right path after their leader is gone? When the Prophet Muhammad passed away, some companions were in denial, but Abu Bakr reminded them: 'Whoever worshipped Muhammad, let him know that Muhammad has died. And whoever worshipped Allah, let him know that Allah is Ever-Living and never dies.'"
  },
  9: {
    "Then We fulfilled Our promise to them": "Allah always keeps His promises. He promised the prophets victory and support, and He delivered. Noah was saved from the flood, Abraham from the fire, Moses from Pharaoh, and so on. This is reassurance for believers that Allah's promises are true, even when circumstances seem impossible.",
    "saving them along with whoever We willed": "Allah saved the prophets and their faithful followers. Salvation was not random but based on faith and righteousness. Those who believed and followed the prophets were rescued from destruction, demonstrating that true safety lies in obedience to Allah.",
    "and destroying the transgressors": "Those who exceeded all bounds in their disbelief and oppression were destroyed. The word 'transgressors' refers to those who crossed all limits in their rejection of truth and persecution of believers. History is filled with examples—the people of Noah drowned, the people of Lot were overturned, and Pharaoh's army was swallowed by the sea. This is a warning that arrogance and transgression lead to ruin."
  },
  10: {
    "We have surely revealed to you a Book, in which there is glory for you": "Allah addresses the Arabs, telling them that the Quran is a source of honor and distinction for them. It was revealed in their language, through a prophet from among them, elevating their status among nations. Before Islam, the Arabs were largely unknown and divided, but through the Quran, they became leaders of a great civilization. The Quran also contains mention of their affairs, guidance for their lives, and solutions to their problems.",
    "Will you not then understand?": "This is a call to use reason and intellect. How can they reject something that brings them honor, guidance, and success in both worlds? Rejecting the Quran is like rejecting a treasure handed to you freely. Allah appeals to their rational thinking, urging them to reflect on the blessings of this Book."
  },
  11: {
    "˹Imagine˺ how many societies of wrongdoers We have destroyed": "Allah draws attention to the ruins of previous civilizations destroyed for their wrongdoing. The Arabs traveled through the remains of Thamud in the area of Al-Hijr and saw the abandoned dwellings of the people of Lot near the Dead Sea. These were not ancient myths but physical evidence they could see with their own eyes. The destruction was a consequence of persistent injustice and rejection of prophets.",
    "raising up other people after them": "After destroying the wrongdoers, Allah replaced them with new generations. This shows that no nation is indispensable. If one people reject guidance, Allah will bring others who will accept it. This is also a warning: the Meccan pagans could be replaced if they persisted in their rejection."
  },
  12: {
    "When the wrongdoers sensed ˹the arrival of˺ Our torment": "When the punishment of Allah began to descend, these arrogant wrongdoers suddenly felt its reality. All their false sense of security vanished. The word 'sensed' indicates they perceived it with their senses—they saw it, heard it, felt it. At that moment, their denial turned to terror.",
    "they started to run away from their cities": "In panic, they tried to flee their homes and cities, hoping to escape the punishment. But where can one run from the decree of Allah? This scene illustrates the futility of fleeing from divine justice. They had ample time to repent and reform, but they wasted it in arrogance. Now, escape was impossible."
  },
  13: {
    "˹They were told,˺ \"Do not run away!": "This is a mocking address, either from the angels of punishment or as a rhetorical statement from Allah. It highlights the absurdity of their attempt to flee. They spent their lives ignoring warnings, and now at the last moment, they think they can run?",
    "Return to your luxuries and your homes": "They were sarcastically told to go back to the comfortable lives they were so attached to—the wealth, the fine homes, the pleasures they prioritized over faith. This irony emphasizes how their worldly attachments were worthless in the face of divine punishment.",
    "so you may be questioned ˹about your fate˺\"": "The purpose of returning was to face questioning and accountability. Some scholars say this refers to being questioned by the victors after a battle, while others say it refers to the ultimate questioning in the Hereafter. Either way, it underscores that there is no escape from accountability."
  },
  14: {
    "They cried, \"Woe to us!": "Faced with destruction, they finally expressed regret, crying out in despair. The Arabic 'Ya waylana' is an expression of extreme grief and desperation. But this regret came too late—it was not sincere repentance but merely a reaction to punishment.",
    "We have surely been wrongdoers\"": "They confessed their wrongdoing, but this confession at the moment of destruction holds no value. True repentance must come before the punishment arrives. Allah says elsewhere in the Quran that repentance is not accepted when the soul reaches the throat (at death) or when the sun rises from the west (a sign of the end times). This teaches us to repent while we still have time."
  },
  15: {
    "They kept repeating their cry": "Their wailing and cries of 'Woe to us!' continued without ceasing. They could not stop lamenting their fate, but their cries did not help them. Actions speak louder than words, and their lifetime of actions was filled with rejection and wrongdoing.",
    "until We mowed them down, ˹leaving them˺ lifeless": "Allah compares their destruction to harvesting crops—just as a farmer cuts down ripe grain, they were cut down completely. The word 'lifeless' (literally 'extinguished') paints a picture of fire being put out, indicating that their lives, vitality, and civilization were completely ended. Nothing remained of their glory."
  },
  16: {
    "We did not create the heavens and the earth and everything in between for sport": "Allah clarifies that the universe was not created without purpose or as a form of entertainment. Every star, every planet, every creature has a purpose. The heavens and earth testify to Allah's power and wisdom. Humans were created to worship Allah and be tested. Life is not a game but a serious journey with eternal consequences. This verse refutes those who think existence is random or meaningless."
  },
  17: {
    "Had We intended to take ˹some˺ amusement, We could have found it in Our presence": "This is a hypothetical statement emphasizing that Allah is far above needing entertainment or amusement. If, hypothetically, Allah wanted amusement, He would not need to create the complex universe for it. He has what is with Him—the angels who constantly glorify Him, the treasures of the unseen, the infinite attributes of perfection.",
    "if that had been Our Will": "But such a thing is not befitting of Allah's majesty. He is the Most High, free from all deficiencies and needs. This phrase negates the entire hypothetical, confirming that Allah never intended any such thing. Creation has a noble purpose: to manifest Allah's names and attributes, to test humanity, and to establish justice."
  },
  18: {
    "In fact, We hurl the truth against falsehood": "Allah presents a powerful image of truth being launched like a projectile against falsehood. Truth is not passive; it actively confronts and destroys lies. The Quran is this truth, refuting the false beliefs of polytheism, atheism, and every deviant ideology. When truth arrives, falsehood cannot stand.",
    "leaving it crushed": "The impact is devastating to falsehood. The Arabic word 'yadmaghuhu' means to strike the head and crush it. Falsehood may seem powerful temporarily, but when confronted with truth, it crumbles. History has shown how Islam defeated the sophisticated falsehoods of its time and continues to provide answers to modern doubts.",
    "and it quickly vanishes": "Falsehood has no substance; it is like a bubble that bursts when touched. No matter how large or intimidating it appears, it cannot survive the encounter with truth. This gives believers confidence: stand firm on truth, and falsehood will eventually disappear.",
    "And woe be to you for what you claim!": "This is a severe warning to those who attribute false things to Allah—whether claiming He has children, partners, or that He created without purpose. Their false claims will bring them destruction. The word 'woe' (wayl) indicates severe punishment and regret."
  },
  19: {
    "To Him belong all those in the heavens and the earth": "Everything and everyone belongs to Allah as His creation and property. The angels in the heavens, humans on earth, jinn, animals, plants—all are His. No one exists independently of Him. This ownership means He has full authority over all, and all will return to Him.",
    "And those nearest to Him are not too proud to worship Him": "The angels who are closest to Allah—those who bear the Throne, Jibreel, Mikael, and others—never consider themselves too great to worship Allah. Despite their elevated status and immense power, they remain humble servants. If such noble beings worship Allah without pride, how can any human consider themselves above worship?",
    "nor do they tire": "The angels never become exhausted or bored with worship. They do not need rest or breaks. Their worship is continuous and joyful. This contrasts with human weakness—we get tired, distracted, and sometimes feel burdened by worship. But even with our limitations, we are called to worship sincerely, and Allah appreciates our efforts."
  },
  20: {
    "They glorify ˹Him˺ day and night": "The angels praise and glorify Allah continuously, throughout the day and night without interruption. Their glorification is their nature and their joy. The Prophet (peace be upon him) mentioned that the angels' tasbeeh (glorification) is like breathing to them—natural and constant.",
    "never wavering": "They never slow down, never take breaks, never become inconsistent in their worship. This is the standard of devotion in the unseen world. While humans cannot match this level of continuous worship, we are encouraged to be consistent in our acts of worship, doing what we can regularly rather than in bursts followed by neglect. The Prophet said, 'The most beloved deeds to Allah are those done consistently, even if they are small.'"
  },
  21: {
    "Or have they taken gods from the earth": "Allah questions the pagans about their choice of deities. They took gods made from earthly materials—stones, wood, metals—or they worshipped beings that lived on earth like humans, jinn, or ancestors. These 'gods' were created things, limited and weak.",
    "who can raise the dead?": "The ultimate test of divinity is the power to give life. Can these so-called gods raise the dead? Can they bring a single deceased person back to life? Of course not. They cannot create a fly, let alone resurrect the dead. Only Allah has this power. On the Day of Judgment, Allah will raise all of creation, but the false gods will be powerless, themselves raised to be judged."
  },
  22: {
    "Had there been other gods besides Allah in the heavens or the earth, both ˹realms˺ would have surely been corrupted": "This is a powerful logical argument against polytheism. If there were multiple gods, each with their own will and power, they would inevitably conflict. One might want the sun to rise while another wants darkness; one might want rain while another wants drought. The universe would fall into chaos. But we observe a perfectly ordered universe operating by consistent laws—proof that only One God controls it all. This argument is called 'Burhan al-Tamanu' (the proof of mutual hindrance).",
    "So Glorified is Allah, Lord of the Throne": "Allah is far above and free from the partners and deficiencies they attribute to Him. He is the Lord of the Throne, the greatest of all creation, which encompasses the heavens and the earth. His sovereignty is absolute and unchallenged.",
    "far above what they claim": "Whatever false descriptions the polytheists give to Allah—whether attributing partners, children, or human limitations—Allah is infinitely exalted above all of it. Their claims are baseless lies that will not harm Allah but will harm those who make them."
  },
  23: {
    "He cannot be questioned about what He does": "Allah, due to His perfect wisdom, complete knowledge, and absolute authority, is not accountable to anyone. No one has the right to question why He decrees something or how He manages the universe. This does not mean His actions are arbitrary—everything He does is based on perfect wisdom, even if we cannot understand it. Just as a patient does not question a skilled surgeon during an operation, we trust Allah's wisdom in all His decisions.",
    "but they will ˹all˺ be questioned": "Unlike Allah, all of creation—humans, jinn, and even the false gods they worshipped—will be questioned. On the Day of Judgment, everyone will be asked about their beliefs, actions, and choices. This verse establishes the fundamental difference between the Creator and creation: He is the Judge, and we are the judged."
  },
  24: {
    "Or have they taken other gods besides Him?": "Allah again questions the polytheists about their choice to worship others alongside or instead of Him. This repetition emphasizes the absurdity of their position and invites them to reflect.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Show ˹me˺ your proof\"": "The Prophet is commanded to challenge them to provide evidence for their beliefs. Faith in Islam is not blind; it is based on clear proofs and sound reasoning. If they claim their gods are worthy of worship, they must provide evidence. But they have none—no logical argument, no scriptural proof, no miraculous sign supporting their polytheism.",
    "Here is ˹the Quran,˺ the Reminder for those with me": "The Quran is presented as evidence. It is the reminder and proof for the Muslims and all who come after. Its miraculous nature, preserved text, and transformative message are proof of its divine origin.",
    "along with ˹earlier Scriptures,˺ the Reminder for those before me": "The previous scriptures—the Torah, the Psalms, the Gospel—also testified to the Oneness of God. Moses, David, and Jesus all called to monotheism. So both past and present revelations unite on this fundamental truth: there is only One God worthy of worship.",
    "But most of them do not know the truth, so they turn away": "The majority remain ignorant of this truth, not because evidence is lacking but because they refuse to sincerely seek it. Their turning away is willful, based on following desires and traditions rather than truth. Ignorance combined with arrogance is a dangerous combination."
  },
  25: {
    "We never sent a messenger before you ˹O Prophet˺ without revealing to him": "This verse establishes the universal message of all prophets throughout history. From Adam to Muhammad (peace be upon them all), every messenger received the same fundamental revelation.",
    "\"There is no god ˹worthy of worship˺ except Me": "This is 'La ilaha illa Allah'—the declaration of monotheism. It means that no one deserves worship, devotion, love, fear, or hope except Allah alone. Not idols, not angels, not prophets, not saints, not nature, not money, not desires—only Allah.",
    "so worship Me ˹alone˺\"": "The logical conclusion of monotheism is exclusive worship of Allah. If He alone is God, then He alone deserves our prayers, our sacrifices, our obedience, and our love. This message united all prophets and their followers. Noah said it, Abraham said it, Moses said it, Jesus said it, and Muhammad said it. It is the thread that connects all divine guidance throughout human history."
  },
  26: {
    "And they say, \"The Most Compassionate has offspring!\"": "Some of the Arab pagans claimed that the angels were daughters of Allah. This was a deeply offensive and illogical claim. They themselves despised having daughters and would bury them alive, yet they attributed daughters to Allah. Other groups, like some Christians, claimed Jesus was the son of God. All such claims are fundamentally flawed because Allah is Self-Sufficient and has no need for offspring. Having children implies incompleteness—a need for heirs, helpers, or continuation. Allah is eternal, all-powerful, and needs nothing.",
    "Glory be to Him!": "This phrase 'Subhanahu' declares Allah's absolute perfection and freedom from any deficiency or false attribution. He is far exalted above having children, partners, or any similarity to His creation. This is a statement of purification (tanzih), cleansing the concept of God from all inappropriate descriptions.",
    "In fact, those ˹angels˺ are only ˹His˺ honoured servants": "The angels, whom they called Allah's children, are in reality His honored servants. They are noble and elevated in status, but they remain servants and creations of Allah. Being honored does not make them divine or related to Allah by family. A king may honor his servants, but that does not make them his sons. The angels' honor comes from their obedience and closeness to Allah, not from any family relationship."
  },
  27: {
    "who do not speak until He has spoken": "The angels do not initiate speech before Allah. They wait for His command and permission before saying anything. This demonstrates their complete submission and respect. Unlike humans who often speak out of turn or offer unsolicited opinions, the angels maintain perfect discipline. They only convey what Allah permits them to convey.",
    "˹only˺ acting at His command": "Every action the angels take is in accordance with Allah's orders. They do not act independently or based on their own desires. Jibreel delivers revelation when commanded, the angel of death takes souls when commanded, and the angels recording deeds write what they are commanded to record. This complete obedience proves they are servants, not children or partners of Allah."
  },
  28: {
    "He ˹fully˺ knows what is ahead of them and what is behind them": "Allah has complete knowledge of everything concerning the angels—their past, present, and future. Nothing about them is hidden from Him. While they are powerful beings, Allah's knowledge encompasses them entirely. This further establishes His supremacy over them.",
    "They do not intercede except for whom He approves": "The pagans believed their idols and the angels could intercede for them with Allah unconditionally. But intercession (shafa'ah) belongs entirely to Allah. The angels can only intercede for those whom Allah permits and approves. On the Day of Judgment, even the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) will seek Allah's permission before interceding. This destroys the false hope of those who worship others expecting automatic intercession.",
    "and they tremble in awe of Him": "Despite their high status and closeness to Allah, the angels are filled with fear and reverence of Him. The Prophet (peace be upon him) described that when Allah speaks with revelation, the angels hear it and fall into prostration out of awe. If the most honored servants of Allah fear Him so much, how much more should humans fear Him and take their worship seriously?"
  },
  29: {
    "Whoever of them were to say, \"I am a god besides Him,\"": "This is a hypothetical scenario. If any angel were to claim divinity—which they never would because of their complete submission—they would face severe punishment. This hypothetical proves that even the highest creation is subject to Allah's authority and judgment. No being, no matter how powerful or close to Allah, can claim divinity.",
    "they would be rewarded with Hell by Us": "The consequence of such a claim would be Hell. The word 'rewarded' is used sarcastically—instead of reward, they would receive punishment. This shows that claiming divinity or partnership with Allah is the greatest crime, deserving the severest punishment.",
    "This is how We reward the wrongdoers": "Allah generalizes the principle: anyone who commits this ultimate wrong—claiming to be a god or setting up partners with Allah—will face Hell. Whether angel, jinn, or human, the punishment for shirk (associating partners with Allah) is the same. This is the ultimate justice."
  },
  30: {
    "Do the disbelievers not realize that the heavens and earth were ˹once˺ one mass then We split them apart?": "Allah draws attention to a profound cosmic fact. The heavens and earth were once joined together as a single entity, and Allah separated them. Modern science speaks of the Big Bang theory, describing how the universe began from a singularity and expanded. While the Quran is not a science textbook, this verse points to Allah's creative power in originating the universe. The separation could refer to the separation of the sky from the earth, or the sending down of rain from the sky to bring life to the earth. Either way, it is a sign of Allah's power.",
    "And We created from water every living thing": "Water is the basis of all life. Every living creature—humans, animals, plants, and microorganisms—depends on water for survival. The human body is about 60% water, and all biological processes require it. This scientific fact, mentioned 1400 years ago, invites reflection on Allah's wisdom in creation. Water is so common that we take it for granted, but it is the essential ingredient for life itself.",
    "Will they not then believe?": "After presenting these clear signs in creation, Allah asks why they still refuse to believe. The evidence is all around them—in the sky above, the earth below, and in their own bodies. Their disbelief is not due to lack of proof but due to stubbornness and unwillingness to submit."
  },
  31: {
    "And We have placed firm mountains upon the earth so it does not shake with them": "Mountains serve as stabilizers for the earth's crust. They have deep roots that anchor the earth's plates, reducing seismic activity and providing stability. Without these natural anchors, the earth would be far more unstable. Modern geology confirms that mountains play a role in stabilizing the earth's surface. This is another sign of Allah's design—nothing in creation is random or purposeless.",
    "and made in it broad pathways so they may find their way": "Allah also created valleys, passes, and pathways between mountains so that people and animals can travel and find their way. Before modern transportation, these natural routes were essential for trade, migration, and communication. This provision shows Allah's mercy in not only creating the world but making it navigable and livable for His creatures."
  },
  32: {
    "And We have made the sky a well-protected canopy": "The sky, or atmosphere, serves as a protective shield for the earth. It protects us from harmful solar radiation, meteors (most of which burn up in the atmosphere), and the extreme cold of space. The ozone layer filters ultraviolet rays, and the magnetic field deflects solar winds. This \"roof\" is perfectly designed to sustain life on earth. It is a canopy that we live under every day without appreciating its protective function.",
    "still they turn away from its signs": "Despite this magnificent sign being visible every time they look up, the disbelievers ignore it. They see the sky, benefit from its protection, yet fail to recognize the Creator behind it. This turning away is willful blindness—the signs are clear, but they choose not to reflect."
  },
  33: {
    "And He is the One Who created the day and the night": "The alternation of day and night is a fundamental aspect of life on earth. Day allows for work, vision, and activity, while night provides rest, sleep, and recovery. This cycle regulates all life—plants, animals, and humans depend on it. The perfect balance between day and night, varying with seasons, is another sign of deliberate design.",
    "the sun and the moon": "The sun provides light, heat, and energy essential for life. The moon illuminates the night, affects the tides, and helps in calculating months and calendars. Both celestial bodies have precise roles in sustaining life on earth. The Arabs used the lunar calendar, so the moon was especially significant for them.",
    "each travelling in an orbit": "Both the sun and moon move in precise, calculated orbits. The moon orbits the earth, and the earth (along with the entire solar system) moves in its orbit around the galactic center. The Arabic word 'yasbahoon' (swimming/floating) beautifully describes their smooth, continuous motion through space. This precision—maintained for billions of years without collision or deviation—points to a Supreme Controller. No random process could maintain such perfect celestial mechanics."
  },
  34: {
    "We have not granted immortality to any human before you ˹O Prophet˺": "No human being in history has been granted eternal life in this world—not Adam, not Noah, not Abraham, not Moses, not any prophet or king. Every human, no matter how great, must taste death. This is a universal law that applies to all of creation. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) is no exception; he too was mortal.",
    "so if you die, will they live forever?": "This is addressed to the disbelievers who seemed to be waiting for the Prophet to die, thinking that would end Islam. Allah asks them: even if the Prophet dies, do they think they will escape death? They too will die and face Allah. The death of the Prophet would not invalidate his message or save them from accountability. In fact, after the Prophet passed away, Islam spread even further across the world."
  },
  35: {
    "Every soul will taste death": "This is one of the most definitive statements in the Quran. Death is not just for the old or the sick—every living soul will experience it. The rich and poor, the powerful and weak, the believers and disbelievers—all will taste death. The word 'taste' implies that death is just a brief experience, a transition to the eternal life that follows. This verse encourages preparation for the inevitable.",
    "And We test you ˹O humanity˺ with good and evil as a trial": "Life is a test, and the test comes in different forms. Sometimes Allah tests with hardship—illness, poverty, loss—to see if we remain patient and grateful. Other times, He tests with blessings—wealth, health, success—to see if we remain humble and obedient. Both are trials. Many people fail the test of blessings more than the test of hardship, becoming arrogant or forgetful of Allah when things go well.",
    "then to Us you will ˹all˺ be returned": "After the test of life and the experience of death, all souls will return to Allah for the final accounting. There is no escape and no alternative destination. This return is certain, and it should motivate us to prepare by living righteously."
  },
  36: {
    "When the disbelievers see you ˹O Prophet˺, they only make fun of you": "The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) faced constant mockery from the Meccan pagans. Instead of engaging with his message, they resorted to ridicule. This is a common tactic of those who cannot refute the truth—they mock the messenger to avoid addressing the message. The Prophet endured this with patience, and Allah comforted him with these verses.",
    "˹saying,˺ \"Is this the one who speaks ˹ill˺ of your gods?\"": "The disbelievers would point at the Prophet and sarcastically ask if this was the man who criticized their idols. To them, criticizing their false gods was a grave offense. They were more protective of their idols than of the truth. Their attachment to false worship blinded them to the reality that their gods could not help or harm anyone.",
    "while they disbelieve at the mention of the Most Compassionate": "The irony is striking: they were offended when their powerless idols were criticized, yet they rejected Ar-Rahman—the Most Compassionate, the true God who created them, sustains them, and will judge them. They defended stones while denying the Lord of the universe. This reveals misplaced loyalty and spiritual blindness."
  },
  37: {
    "Humankind is made of haste": "Human beings are naturally impatient. We want things immediately—results, answers, gratification. This impatience often leads to poor decisions and regret. The disbelievers were hastily demanding the punishment they were warned about, not realizing what they were asking for. Allah describes this as a fundamental human trait that needs to be controlled through faith and wisdom.",
    "I will soon show you My signs, so do not ask Me to hasten them": "Allah warns them that His signs—whether signs of guidance or signs of punishment—will come at the appointed time. Their mocking requests to hasten the punishment would be answered, but when it comes, they will wish it had never arrived. Allah operates according to His perfect wisdom and timing, not according to human impatience."
  },
  38: {
    "They ask ˹the believers˺, \"When will this threat come to pass if what you say is true?\"": "The disbelievers would taunt the Muslims, demanding to know when the promised punishment or Day of Judgment would arrive. They asked this mockingly, not sincerely. They thought the delay in punishment meant it would never come. But Allah gives respite so that people have time to repent. The delay is mercy, not weakness. When the punishment finally comes, there will be no more chances."
  },
  39: {
    "If only the disbelievers knew that a time will come when they will not be able to keep the Fire off their faces or backs": "Allah describes the helplessness of the disbelievers in Hell. The Fire will attack them from all directions—their faces and backs—and they will have no way to protect themselves. No shields, no barriers, no escape. The very faces that smiled in mockery and the backs that turned away from truth will be exposed to the Fire.",
    "nor will they be helped": "On that Day, no one will come to their aid. The idols they worshipped will be useless. Their wealth and status will mean nothing. The allies and friends who supported them in worldly life will flee from them. Every person will be concerned only with themselves. This absolute helplessness is the consequence of rejecting Allah's guidance."
  },
  40: {
    "In fact, the Hour will take them by surprise": "The Day of Judgment will not come with advance warning or gradual signs that allow preparation. It will come suddenly, when people are busy with their daily lives—buying, selling, eating, planning for the future. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said the Hour will come upon people while a man is milking his camel or setting up his business, and it will overtake them before they can finish.",
    "leaving them stunned": "The suddenness will leave them in complete shock and confusion. All their arrogance, all their mockery, all their denial will vanish in an instant, replaced by terror and disbelief at what is happening. They spent their lives denying this Day, and suddenly it is upon them.",
    "So they will not be able to avert it": "There will be no way to stop, delay, or prevent the Hour once it arrives. No technology, no power, no plea will change anything. The decree of Allah will be executed precisely as He willed.",
    "nor will it be delayed from them": "They will not be given extra time or a grace period. The jokes and demands to hasten the punishment will be answered in full, with no extensions. This is why the time to prepare is now, while we are still alive and have the opportunity to repent and do good."
  },
  41: {
    "˹Other˺ messengers had already been ridiculed before you ˹O Prophet˺": "Allah comforts the Prophet by reminding him that mockery of messengers is not new. Noah was mocked for building the ark, Abraham was ridiculed for rejecting idols, Moses was laughed at by Pharaoh, and every prophet faced similar treatment. The Prophet is in noble company, and their example shows that mockery does not diminish the truth.",
    "but those who mocked them were overtaken by what they used to ridicule": "The very punishment they mocked and demanded came upon them. The flood they laughed at drowned them. The fire they denied burned them. The earthquake they dismissed destroyed them. This historical pattern is a warning: those who mock divine warnings eventually face those exact consequences. The Meccan pagans would be no exception."
  },
  42: {
    "Ask ˹them, O Prophet,˺ \"Who can defend you by day or by night against the Most Compassionate?\"": "This is a powerful rhetorical question. If Allah, the Most Compassionate, decides to punish them, who can protect them? Not their idols, not their ancestors, not their wealth or armies. Allah's power is absolute, and no one can shield someone from His decree. The question exposes the complete helplessness of those who rely on anything other than Allah.",
    "Still they turn away from the remembrance of their Lord": "Despite knowing deep down that their idols are powerless, they continue to ignore and turn away from Allah's remembrance. The Quran, the Prophet's teachings, and the signs in creation all call them to remember their Lord, but they stubbornly refuse. This turning away is the root cause of their spiritual destruction."
  },
  43: {
    "Or do they have gods—other than Us—that can protect them?": "Another rhetorical question challenging them to produce evidence of their gods' power. Can these idols protect their worshippers from Allah's punishment? The answer is obviously no. The idols are inanimate objects or powerless beings that cannot even hear prayers, let alone answer them.",
    "They cannot ˹even˺ protect themselves": "The false gods cannot even protect themselves. An idol can be broken, stolen, or destroyed—it cannot defend itself. How then can it defend its worshippers? This logical argument exposes the absurdity of worshipping created things that are weaker than their worshippers.",
    "nor will they be aided against Us": "On the Day of Judgment, these false gods will not receive any assistance. They will not be able to help themselves or their worshippers. In fact, they will be questioned about the worship directed to them, and they will disown their worshippers."
  },
  44: {
    "In fact, We have allowed enjoyment for these ˹Meccans˺ and their forefathers for such a long time ˹that they took it for granted˺": "Allah explains that the Meccans' prosperity and long lives deceived them. Because punishment did not come immediately, they thought it would never come. They assumed their comfortable lives were a sign of being right. But Allah gives respite; He allows enjoyment as a test. Many generations passed in comfort, leading them to become complacent and arrogant.",
    "Do they not see that We gradually reduce ˹their˺ land from its borders?": "Allah points to the gradual reduction of their power and territory. Some scholars say this refers to the Muslim conquests that were to come, gradually taking land from the pagans. Others say it refers to death taking people from the edges of society. Either way, signs of their decline were visible for those who chose to see.",
    "Is it they who will then prevail?": "Given these signs of decline, do they really think they will be victorious against Allah and His messenger? Their assumption of eternal dominance is delusional. History has shown that those who oppose Allah's messengers are eventually defeated."
  },
  45: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"I warn you only by revelation.\"": "The Prophet clarifies his role: he is a warner who conveys what Allah has revealed to him. He does not speak from his own desires or create warnings from his imagination. Every warning comes from divine revelation, which is the highest authority. This emphasizes the credibility and seriousness of the message.",
    "But the deaf cannot hear the call when they are warned!": "This is a metaphor for spiritual deafness. The disbelievers are not physically deaf, but they have closed their hearts to the message. No matter how clearly the warning is delivered, they do not hear it because they refuse to. It is like shouting to someone who has plugged their ears—the sound reaches them, but they do not listen. This spiritual condition is self-inflicted and is more severe than physical deafness."
  },
  46: {
    "If they were touched by even a breath of your Lord's torment": "Allah describes His punishment as so severe that even a tiny portion of it—a mere breath or whiff—would be unbearable. The word 'nafha' suggests the lightest touch, yet even this would overwhelm them. This indicates that the full punishment is beyond human comprehension.",
    "they would certainly cry, \"Woe to us! We have really been wrongdoers.\"": "If even a small portion of the punishment touched them, they would immediately confess their wrongdoing. The same people who arrogantly rejected the message and mocked the Prophet would be crying out in regret. But this confession at the time of punishment is too late—sincere repentance must come before the punishment arrives, not after."
  },
  47: {
    "We will set up the scales of justice on the Day of Judgment": "On the Day of Resurrection, Allah will establish scales to weigh people's deeds. These scales are real, though we cannot comprehend their exact nature. They will measure good deeds against bad deeds with absolute precision. The concept of scales emphasizes fairness—everyone will be judged by the same standard.",
    "so no soul will be wronged in the least": "Allah's justice is perfect. No one will be treated unfairly—not a single atom's weight of injustice will occur. Good deeds will not be lost or diminished, and no one will be punished for sins they did not commit. This assurance gives believers hope and warns wrongdoers that they cannot escape accountability.",
    "And ˹even˺ if a deed is the weight of a mustard seed, We will bring it forth": "Even the tiniest deed—as small as a mustard seed, one of the smallest seeds known—will be brought forth and accounted for. Nothing is too small to be recorded. A kind word, a small charity, a brief moment of remembering Allah—all are recorded. Likewise, a small sin, a moment of arrogance, a hurtful glance—nothing escapes. This should motivate us to maximize good deeds and avoid even 'small' sins.",
    "And sufficient are We as a ˹vigilant˺ Reckoner": "Allah is the best and most accurate accountant. He does not need helpers or calculators. His knowledge is perfect, His justice is flawless, and His reckoning is complete. This phrase assures believers that their good deeds will not be lost and warns disbelievers that their crimes will not be forgotten."
  },
  48: {
    "Indeed, We granted Moses and Aaron the standard ˹to distinguish between right and wrong˺": "Allah gave Moses and Aaron the Torah, which served as a 'Furqan'—a criterion to distinguish truth from falsehood, right from wrong, and guidance from misguidance. This scripture provided clear standards for the Children of Israel to live by. The concept of Furqan applies to all divine books, including the Quran.",
    "a light and a reminder for the righteous": "The Torah was a source of light, illuminating the path of righteousness in times of spiritual darkness. It was also a reminder, bringing people back to consciousness of Allah and their duties to Him. However, this light and reminder benefit only the righteous—those who approach scripture with sincere hearts seeking guidance."
  },
  49: {
    "who are in awe of their Lord without seeing Him": "The righteous are those who fear Allah even though they cannot see Him. They do not need to witness Allah directly to believe in Him and obey Him. Their faith is in the unseen—they trust in Allah's existence, His attributes, and His promises based on the signs and revelations He has provided. This is the essence of true faith.",
    "and are fearful of the Hour": "They also live with awareness of the Day of Judgment. This fear is not paralyzing terror but a motivating awareness that keeps them on the straight path. They prepare for that Day by doing good deeds and avoiding sins. The combination of fearing Allah and fearing the Hour produces righteous action."
  },
  50: {
    "And this ˹Quran˺ is a blessed reminder which We have revealed": "After mentioning the Torah, Allah now speaks about the Quran. It is described as 'mubarak' (blessed)—full of goodness, benefit, and divine favor. Every letter of the Quran carries reward, every verse contains guidance, and every chapter brings light. It is a reminder that awakens hearts and brings people back to their Lord. Unlike previous scriptures that were altered over time, the Quran is preserved and will remain a source of guidance until the end of time.",
    "Will you ˹pagans˺ then deny it?": "This is a direct challenge to the Meccan pagans. Given the Quran's clear guidance, its miraculous nature, and its consistency with previous revelations, how can they reject it? Their denial is unreasonable and self-destructive. The question implies that accepting the Quran is the only logical and beneficial choice. This challenge remains open to all people in all times: will you embrace this blessed reminder or turn away from it?"
  },
  51: {
    "And indeed, We had granted Abraham sound judgment early on": "Allah blessed Abraham with 'rushd'—sound judgment, right guidance, and spiritual maturity—from a young age. Unlike many who find guidance later in life, Abraham was granted this wisdom early, allowing him to recognize the falsehood of idol worship while still young. This early guidance prepared him for his mission as the father of prophets and a leader for humanity. It shows that Allah prepares His chosen servants from the beginning of their lives.",
    "for We knew him well ˹to be worthy of it˺": "Allah's knowledge is perfect and eternal. He knew Abraham's sincerity, courage, and potential before Abraham even demonstrated these qualities publicly. Allah grants guidance to those He knows are worthy of it and will use it properly. This is not favoritism but divine wisdom—Allah places responsibility on those capable of bearing it."
  },
  52: {
    "˹Remember˺ when he questioned his father and his people": "Abraham did not remain silent about the falsehood around him. Despite the potential consequences of challenging his own family and community, he spoke up. This took immense courage, as his father Azar was himself an idol-maker. Prophets are not passive observers; they actively engage with their societies to guide them to truth.",
    "\"What are these statues to which you are so devoted?\"": "Abraham asked a penetrating question designed to make them think. The word 'devoted' (akifoon) implies they were constantly attending to these statues, spending time, resources, and emotion on them. Abraham wanted them to articulate why they worshipped these inanimate objects. Often, when people are forced to explain illogical beliefs, they realize their absurdity. This is the Socratic method of questioning—leading people to truth through thoughtful questions."
  },
  53: {
    "They replied, \"We found our forefathers worshipping them.\"": "Their only justification was tradition—they did it because their ancestors did it. This is one of the weakest arguments for any belief or practice. Blind following of ancestors without questioning is dangerous because ancestors can be wrong. Many evils throughout history have been justified by 'tradition.' Islam teaches that we must evaluate inherited beliefs against reason and revelation. If our ancestors were right, we follow them; if they were wrong, we must have the courage to break from them."
  },
  54: {
    "He responded, \"Indeed, you and your forefathers have been clearly astray.\"": "Abraham did not soften his message to avoid conflict. He directly told them that both they and their ancestors were in clear misguidance. This was not disrespect but honesty. A doctor who diagnoses a serious illness is not being cruel by telling the truth—withholding the diagnosis would be the real cruelty. Similarly, telling people they are on the wrong path is an act of mercy, not hostility. The truth sometimes hurts, but it is necessary for correction."
  },
  55: {
    "They asked, \"Have you come to us with the truth, or is this a joke?\"": "They could not believe someone would seriously challenge their ancient traditions. To them, questioning idol worship was either revolutionary truth or complete madness. This reaction is common when people hear something that contradicts their deeply held beliefs—they dismiss it as a joke or the words of a crazy person. They could not fathom that their entire religious system was false, so they assumed Abraham must be joking."
  },
  56: {
    "He replied, \"In fact, your Lord is the Lord of the heavens and the earth, Who created them ˹both˺\"": "Abraham presented the logical argument for monotheism. The true Lord is not these man-made statues but the Creator of the heavens and the earth. The One who created the universe is the only One worthy of worship. These idols did not create anything—they were themselves created by human hands. This argument from creation is powerful: the Creator has rights over the created; the created cannot have rights over its own maker.",
    "And to that I bear witness": "Abraham declared himself a witness to this truth. He was not uncertain or doubtful—he testified with complete conviction. A witness speaks from knowledge and certainty. Abraham's witness was based on his observation of the universe and his innate recognition (fitrah) of the One Creator. This declaration also made him legally accountable for his statement, showing his sincerity."
  },
  57: {
    "˹Then he said to himself,˺ \"By Allah! I will surely plot against your idols after you have turned your backs and gone away.\"": "Abraham made a solemn oath to take action against the idols. He waited for the right opportunity—when the people would leave for their festival—to carry out his plan. This shows strategic thinking; he did not act impulsively but planned carefully. His 'plot' was not malicious scheming but a practical demonstration to prove the powerlessness of the idols. Sometimes actions speak louder than words, and Abraham was about to give his people an unforgettable lesson."
  },
  58: {
    "So he smashed them into pieces": "Abraham took an axe and destroyed the idols, reducing them to fragments. This was a bold and dangerous act of civil disobedience against the established religion of his society. He demonstrated that these 'gods' could not even protect themselves from a single young man. If they could not prevent their own destruction, how could they help or harm their worshippers?",
    "except the biggest of them": "Abraham deliberately left the largest idol intact. This was part of his plan to force the people to confront the truth. By leaving one idol standing, he created a situation where he could ask them to question that idol about what happened. This set up the logical trap he would spring later.",
    "so they might turn to it ˹for answers˺": "He hoped the people would ask the remaining idol who destroyed the others. When the idol could not answer—because it was just a statue—they would be forced to acknowledge its powerlessness. Abraham was using their own beliefs against them to expose the absurdity of idol worship."
  },
  59: {
    "They protested, \"Who dared do this to our gods?": "When the people returned and found their idols destroyed, they were outraged. They immediately asked who committed this 'crime.' Notice how they called the statues 'our gods'—they claimed ownership over their deities, which is itself absurd. How can one own a god? Their attachment to these idols was emotional, not rational.",
    "It must be an evildoer!\"": "They labeled the unknown perpetrator an evildoer (zalim—wrongdoer). In their twisted worldview, breaking idols was a terrible crime, while worshipping stones was righteousness. This inversion of values is common when people stray from truth—they call good evil and evil good. The real wrongdoing was their worship of false gods, not Abraham's destruction of them."
  },
  60: {
    "Some said, \"We heard a young man, called Abraham, speaking ˹ill˺ of them.\"": "Someone remembered that a young man named Abraham had been publicly criticizing the idols. His earlier questioning and declaration had not gone unnoticed. This is a reminder that speaking truth in public has consequences—people will remember and hold you accountable. Abraham's courage to speak openly now made him the prime suspect. But he was ready to face the consequences of his convictions."
  },
  61: {
    "They demanded, \"Bring him before the eyes of the people, so that they may witness ˹his trial˺.\"": "The leaders wanted a public trial to make an example of Abraham. They gathered the people to witness the confrontation, thinking this would humiliate Abraham and reinforce their authority. Little did they know that this public platform would backfire—Abraham would use it to expose the truth to everyone. Allah often turns the plans of the disbelievers against them."
  },
  62: {
    "They asked, \"Was it you who did this to our gods, O Abraham?\"": "In front of the assembled crowd, they directly accused Abraham. This was his moment of truth. He could have denied it out of fear, but Abraham had a more clever response prepared. The public nature of the question required a public answer that would make everyone think."
  },
  63: {
    "He replied ˹sarcastically˺, \"No, this one—the biggest of them—did it!": "Abraham gave a brilliant response. He pointed to the large idol he had deliberately left standing and attributed the destruction to it. This was not a lie but a rhetorical device—a reductio ad absurdum. He was saying: 'If these idols are really gods with power and will, then surely the biggest one could have done this.' Of course, everyone knew the idol could not have done it, which was exactly Abraham's point.",
    "So ask them, if they can talk!\"": "Abraham challenged them to ask the idols themselves. This was the knockout punch. If these are really gods, they should be able to speak, explain what happened, and identify the perpetrator. The inability of the idols to respond would prove they were powerless objects, not divine beings. Abraham turned his trial into a trial of the idols."
  },
  64: {
    "So they came back to their senses, saying ˹to one another˺, \"You yourselves are truly the wrongdoers!\"": "For a moment, Abraham's logic penetrated their hearts. They realized the truth—they were the wrongdoers for worshipping these powerless statues. They turned to each other in acknowledgment of their error. This brief moment of clarity shows that deep down, the human fitrah (innate nature) recognizes truth when presented clearly. The conscience cannot be permanently silenced."
  },
  65: {
    "Then they ˹quickly˺ regressed to their ˹original˺ mind-set": "Tragically, the moment of clarity was short-lived. They returned to their previous position, turning away from the truth they had just recognized. The phrase 'nukisu ala ru'usihim' (literally 'turned upside-down on their heads') vividly describes their spiritual regression. Pride, social pressure, and attachment to tradition overcame their reason.",
    "˹arguing,˺ \"You already know that those ˹idols˺ cannot talk.\"": "Now they used the idols' inability to speak as a defense—the very point Abraham was making! They admitted the idols could not talk, which means they admitted the idols were powerless. Yet they still refused to abandon idol worship. This shows how stubbornness can make people cling to falsehood even when they know it is false. They prioritized their pride over the truth."
  },
  66: {
    "He rebuked ˹them˺, \"Do you then worship—instead of Allah—what can neither benefit nor harm you in any way?\"": "Abraham pressed his advantage. Having established that the idols cannot speak, he extended the logic: if they cannot speak, they certainly cannot benefit you or protect you from harm. They cannot answer prayers, provide sustenance, cure illness, or grant success. And they cannot punish those who reject them. So what is the point of worshipping them? Worship should be directed to the One who truly has power over all things—Allah."
  },
  67: {
    "Shame on you and whatever you worship instead of Allah!": "Abraham expressed his disgust and frustration. The Arabic 'uff' is an expression of contempt and exasperation. He was not being disrespectful for the sake of it but expressing righteous anger at the absurdity of their worship. Sometimes, after patient reasoning fails, strong words are needed to shake people out of their complacency.",
    "Do you not have any sense?\"": "He appealed to their reason one final time. The question implies that any thinking person should be able to see the folly of idol worship. Faith in Islam is not blind—it is based on reason and evidence. Abraham demonstrated throughout this encounter that monotheism is the logical conclusion for anyone who thinks deeply about the nature of God and creation."
  },
  68: {
    "They concluded, \"Burn him up to avenge your gods, if you must act.\"": "Unable to defeat Abraham with arguments, they resorted to violence. This is the last refuge of those who have no logical response—they try to silence the truth by eliminating the one who speaks it. They wanted to burn Abraham alive as punishment and as revenge for their destroyed idols. The irony is that their 'gods' needed humans to avenge them—further proof of their powerlessness. A true God does not need human defenders."
  },
  69: {
    "We ordered, \"O fire! Be cool and safe for Abraham!\"": "When Abraham was thrown into the massive fire, Allah commanded the fire to change its nature specifically for him. Fire, which normally burns, became cool and peaceful for Abraham. This is a stunning miracle that demonstrates Allah's absolute control over all creation. The elements of nature obey Allah's command—fire burns only because Allah wills it, and it can cease to burn when He wills otherwise. According to some narrations, Allah commanded the fire to be 'cool' so Abraham would not burn, and 'safe' so the coolness would not harm him either. This perfect balance protected him completely."
  },
  70: {
    "They had sought to harm him": "The disbelievers plotted and planned to destroy Abraham. They built a huge fire, gathered wood for days, and used catapults to throw him in because the fire was too large to approach. All their effort and scheming was directed at eliminating this one man who challenged their false beliefs.",
    "but We made them the worst losers": "Despite all their plotting, they failed completely. Not only did Abraham survive unharmed, but their plan backfired spectacularly. They became the losers—their religion was publicly humiliated, their powerlessness exposed, and Abraham's message was vindicated. This is a recurring pattern: those who plot against Allah's messengers ultimately destroy themselves. The verse reassures believers that no matter how powerful the opposition seems, Allah's plan will prevail."
  },
  71: {
    "Then We delivered him, along with Lot, to the land We had showered with blessings for all people": "After the fire incident, Allah guided Abraham and his nephew Lot to migrate from Iraq to the blessed land of Palestine/Syria (the Levant). This region is called blessed because many prophets lived and preached there, including Abraham, Isaac, Jacob, Joseph, Moses, David, Solomon, Jesus, and others. It is also blessed with natural resources, fertile land, and strategic importance. Migration for the sake of faith (hijrah) is a noble act, and Abraham's migration set a precedent followed by many prophets and believers, including Prophet Muhammad's migration to Madinah."
  },
  72: {
    "And We blessed him with Isaac ˹as a son˺ and Jacob ˹as a grandson˺, as an additional favour": "Allah rewarded Abraham's faith and sacrifice with righteous offspring. Isaac was his son through Sarah, and Jacob (Israel) was his grandson. The word 'nafilah' (additional favor/bonus) indicates that these blessings exceeded Abraham's expectations. He had asked Allah for righteous children, and Allah gave him not just a son but a dynasty of prophets. Ishmael, Abraham's firstborn through Hagar, is not mentioned here because this passage focuses on the lineage through Isaac, but Ishmael was equally blessed as the ancestor of Prophet Muhammad.",
    "making all of them righteous": "Both Isaac and Jacob were not just biologically descended from Abraham but spiritually followed his path. They were righteous prophets who continued his mission of monotheism. This shows that true legacy is not just biological but spiritual—passing on faith and values to the next generation."
  },
  73: {
    "We ˹also˺ made them leaders, guiding by Our command": "Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob were not just personally righteous but were made leaders (imams) for humanity. They guided people to Allah by His command, not by their own invention. True religious leadership is based on divine guidance, not personal opinion or cultural tradition. They led by example and by teaching the revelation they received.",
    "and inspired them to do good deeds": "Allah inspired them with the knowledge and motivation to perform righteous actions. Good deeds are the fruit of faith, and these prophets excelled in every type of goodness—charity, kindness, justice, and service to others.",
    "establish prayer": "Prayer (salah) was a central practice for them, as it is for all prophets. Establishing prayer means not just performing it occasionally but making it a consistent, prioritized part of life, and encouraging others to do the same. Prayer connects the servant to the Lord and provides spiritual strength.",
    "and pay alms-tax": "Zakah (obligatory charity) was also part of their practice. Sharing wealth with those in need purifies the soul from greed and creates a just society. This shows that the fundamental practices of Islam existed in the teachings of all prophets.",
    "And they were devoted to Our worship": "Their entire lives were oriented toward worshipping Allah. Worship was not just a part of their routine but the purpose of their existence. This devotion is the model for all believers."
  },
  74: {
    "And to Lot We gave wisdom and knowledge": "Lot, who was Abraham's nephew and followed him in faith, was also blessed with prophethood. Allah granted him 'hukm' (wisdom, judgment, authority) and 'ilm' (knowledge). These two qualities are essential for any prophet—wisdom to apply knowledge correctly and knowledge to guide people to truth. Lot used these gifts to call his people away from their evil practices.",
    "and delivered him from the society engrossed in shameful practices": "Lot was sent to the people of Sodom and Gomorrah, cities notorious for their open practice of homosexuality and other immoral behaviors. He preached against their sins for years, but they refused to reform. When Allah's punishment came, Lot and his believing family members were saved while the rest were destroyed. Allah protects His righteous servants from the punishment meant for the wicked.",
    "They were certainly an evil, rebellious people": "The people of Lot were not just mistaken but actively evil and rebellious. They committed sins openly, rejected their prophet's warnings, and even threatened Lot for trying to guide them. Their sins were so severe and their arrogance so complete that they earned total destruction—their cities were overturned and rained upon with stones of baked clay."
  },
  75: {
    "And We admitted him into Our mercy": "Allah enveloped Lot in His special mercy. This mercy included protection from the punishment that befell his people, guidance throughout his life, and ultimately, a place in Paradise. Being admitted into Allah's mercy is the ultimate success and the goal of every believer.",
    "˹for˺ he was truly one of the righteous": "Lot is certified by Allah as being among the righteous (saliheen). Despite living among the most corrupt people on earth, he maintained his righteousness and never compromised his principles. This is a powerful example for believers who find themselves surrounded by immorality—one can remain righteous regardless of the environment. Lot stood firm, preached the truth, and was ultimately vindicated. His story encourages Muslims to maintain their values even when they are a minority and to trust that Allah will reward their steadfastness."
  },
  76: {
    "And ˹remember˺ when Noah had cried out to Us earlier": "Noah is mentioned here as another example of a prophet who turned to Allah in desperate times. He called upon Allah after enduring 950 years of preaching to a stubborn people who refused to believe. His supplication came after exhausting all efforts and facing constant rejection, mockery, and threats. This teaches us that turning to Allah in du'a (supplication) is appropriate after making sincere efforts.",
    "so We responded to him": "Allah answered Noah's prayer. This simple statement carries immense weight—the Creator of the universe responds to the sincere call of His servant. No matter how long the wait or how difficult the circumstances, Allah hears and responds. The response may not always be immediate or in the form we expect, but it always comes.",
    "and delivered him and his family from the great distress": "The 'great distress' refers to the flood that destroyed Noah's people and the years of persecution he endured. Allah saved Noah and the believers with him on the ark. His family here refers to those who believed—his wife and one of his sons were not saved because they rejected faith. This shows that salvation is based on faith, not just blood relations."
  },
  77: {
    "And We made him prevail over those who had rejected Our signs": "Allah gave Noah ultimate victory over his opponents. Though he was mocked and opposed for centuries, in the end, he was vindicated. The truth prevailed, and falsehood was destroyed. This is Allah's consistent way—He supports His messengers and grants them victory, even if it takes time.",
    "They were truly an evil people": "Noah's people were not merely mistaken; they were actively evil. They rejected clear signs, mocked the messenger, persecuted believers, and refused to repent despite numerous warnings. Their evil was persistent and defiant.",
    "so We drowned them all": "The punishment was comprehensive—the entire disbelieving population was drowned in the flood. Not a single rejecter survived. This serves as a warning to all future generations: persistent rejection of Allah's guidance leads to destruction. The flood of Noah is mentioned across cultures and religions as a historical event of divine intervention."
  },
  78: {
    "And ˹remember˺ when David and Solomon passed judgment regarding the crops ruined ˹at night˺ by someone's sheep": "This verse refers to a specific case brought before the prophet-kings David and Solomon. A man's sheep had strayed into another man's field at night and destroyed his crops. Both parties came seeking justice. David, as the senior judge, issued his ruling first. This case illustrates that even prophets engage in practical matters of daily life and justice.",
    "and We were witness to their judgments": "Allah was fully aware of both judgments—David's initial ruling and Solomon's alternative suggestion. This statement emphasizes that Allah observes all our decisions and actions. It also validates that both father and son acted sincerely, even though their conclusions differed."
  },
  79: {
    "We guided ˹young˺ Solomon to a fairer settlement": "Allah inspired Solomon with a more equitable solution. According to scholars, David ruled that the sheep should be given to the farmer as compensation for his destroyed crops. Solomon suggested instead that the farmer keep the sheep temporarily to benefit from their milk and wool, while the sheep owner works the damaged land until the crops grow back, then they exchange back. This way, both parties are restored to their original state without permanent loss. This shows Solomon's keen understanding of justice and restoration.",
    "and granted each of them wisdom and knowledge": "Despite Solomon's better solution in this case, Allah affirms that both David and Solomon were blessed with wisdom and knowledge. David was not diminished by his son's insight; both were divinely guided prophets. This teaches humility—even great scholars can learn from others, including their juniors.",
    "We subjected the mountains as well as the birds to hymn ˹Our praises˺ along with David": "David was given a miraculous gift: when he glorified Allah, the mountains and birds would join him in praise. His voice was so beautiful and his worship so sincere that creation itself responded. The Psalms (Zabur) he received were recited with such melodious devotion that all of nature participated. This miracle honored David and demonstrated Allah's control over all creation.",
    "It is We Who did ˹it all˺": "Allah emphasizes that these miracles were His doing, not David's own power. This prevents any misunderstanding that David had independent supernatural abilities. All blessings and miracles come from Allah alone."
  },
  80: {
    "We taught him the art of making body armour": "Allah taught David the craft of making chain mail armor. Before this, armor was made of solid metal plates that were heavy and inflexible. David was inspired to create interlocking metal rings, producing armor that was both protective and flexible. This was a technological advancement given by divine inspiration.",
    "to protect you in battle": "The purpose of this knowledge was practical—to protect soldiers in warfare. Islam acknowledges the reality of conflict and the need for self-defense. Allah provides means for protection, showing His care for human welfare even in difficult circumstances like war.",
    "Will you then be grateful?": "After mentioning this blessing, Allah asks humanity if they will be grateful. Every skill, technology, and knowledge we have ultimately traces back to Allah's teaching and inspiration. Gratitude (shukr) is the appropriate response to recognizing these blessings."
  },
  81: {
    "And to Solomon We subjected the raging winds, blowing by his command": "Solomon was given authority over the winds. He could command powerful winds to carry him and his army wherever he needed to go. This was a unique miracle not given to any other prophet. The wind would transport his throne and entourage across vast distances in short periods. What would take months of travel could be accomplished in a day.",
    "to the land We had showered with blessings": "The winds would carry Solomon to the blessed land of Syria/Palestine, the center of his kingdom. This region is repeatedly called blessed in the Quran due to its significance in prophetic history.",
    "It is We Who know everything": "Allah's knowledge encompasses all things. He knew that Solomon would use these powers responsibly for good purposes. Allah grants special abilities to those He knows will use them properly."
  },
  82: {
    "And ˹We subjected˺ some jinn that dived for him": "Allah also gave Solomon authority over jinn (supernatural beings). Some of these jinn would dive into the seas to retrieve pearls, precious stones, and other treasures for Solomon. This was labor that humans could not perform, demonstrating the vast resources at Solomon's disposal.",
    "and performed other duties": "Beyond diving, the jinn performed various other tasks including construction, craftsmanship, and service. They built magnificent structures for Solomon, including his famous temple. Despite being powerful beings, they were subjugated to serve a human prophet.",
    "It is We Who kept them in check": "Allah maintained control over the jinn, preventing them from harming Solomon or disobeying excessively. Without Allah's protection, these powerful beings could have been dangerous. This reminder emphasizes that Solomon's authority over jinn was a gift from Allah, not his own power, and that Allah remained the ultimate controller."
  },
  83: {
    "And ˹remember˺ when Job cried out to his Lord": "Job (Ayyub) is one of the most famous examples of patience in adversity. He was a wealthy, healthy man with a large family when Allah tested him. He lost his wealth, his children died, and he was afflicted with a severe illness that lasted for years. Throughout this trial, he remained patient and did not complain against Allah's decree.",
    "\"I have been touched with adversity\"": "Notice the beautiful etiquette of Job's supplication. He did not complain or express bitterness. He simply stated his condition—that harm had touched him. He did not attribute the harm to Allah negatively or question divine wisdom. He acknowledged his difficulty while maintaining respect and trust in his Lord. This is the model of how to make du'a during hardship.",
    "and You are the Most Merciful of the merciful": "Job appealed to Allah's mercy rather than demanding relief. He affirmed Allah's attribute of being the Most Merciful, expressing hope and trust rather than desperation or blame. This teaches us that even in our darkest moments, we should remember Allah's beautiful attributes and call upon Him with hope."
  },
  84: {
    "So We answered his prayer and removed his adversity": "Allah responded to Job's humble supplication by completely removing his affliction. According to traditions, Allah commanded Job to strike the ground with his foot, and a spring of healing water emerged. He drank from it and bathed in it, and his health was fully restored. The years of suffering were erased by Allah's mercy.",
    "and gave him back his family, twice as many": "Not only was Job healed, but Allah restored his family and doubled what he had lost. Some scholars say his deceased children were returned to him in the afterlife while he was also blessed with new children in this world. Others say he was given double the number of children. Either way, Allah's compensation exceeded the original loss.",
    "as a mercy from Us": "This restoration was an act of divine mercy, not something Job earned or deserved by his patience. While his patience was exemplary, the reward was still Allah's grace. This teaches us that Allah's mercy is always greater than our efforts.",
    "and a lesson for the ˹devoted˺ worshippers": "Job's story serves as an eternal lesson for all believers. When we face trials, we can remember Job and find strength. If he could remain patient through years of severe illness, loss, and isolation, we can endure our comparatively smaller trials. His story proves that patience is rewarded and that relief comes to those who trust in Allah."
  },
  85: {
    "And ˹remember˺ Ishmael, Enoch, and Ⱬul-Kifl": "Allah mentions three more prophets as examples. Ishmael was Abraham's firstborn son through Hagar, and the ancestor of Prophet Muhammad. He helped his father build the Ka'bah and was known for his patience when his father was commanded to sacrifice him. Enoch (Idris) was an early prophet known for his piety and knowledge, whom Allah raised to a high station. Dhul-Kifl is believed by many scholars to be a prophet, possibly Ezekiel, known for fulfilling his commitments.",
    "They were all steadfast": "The common quality highlighted is 'sabr' (patience/steadfastness). Each of these prophets faced their own trials and remained firm in faith and obedience. Patience is a recurring theme in the stories of prophets because it is essential for enduring the difficulties of conveying Allah's message and facing opposition."
  },
  86: {
    "We admitted them into Our mercy": "Allah enveloped these prophets in His special mercy. This mercy included guidance in this life, protection from enemies, honor among people, and ultimately Paradise in the Hereafter. Being admitted into Allah's mercy is the ultimate success.",
    "for they were truly of the righteous": "Their righteousness earned them this honor. They were not just prophets by title but truly righteous in their character, actions, and devotion to Allah. The title 'saliheen' (righteous) is one of the highest honors mentioned in the Quran."
  },
  87: {
    "And ˹remember˺ when the Man of the Whale stormed off ˹from his city˺ in a rage": "Jonah (Yunus) is called 'Dhun-Nun' (the Man of the Whale/Fish). He was sent to the people of Nineveh (in modern-day Iraq) who rejected his message. Frustrated and angry at their disbelief, Jonah left before Allah gave him permission to do so. His departure was premature—he gave up on his people too soon.",
    "thinking We would not restrain him": "Jonah thought he could leave without consequence, that Allah would not hold him accountable for abandoning his mission. Some scholars interpret this as thinking Allah would not decree difficulty for him. This was a lapse in judgment, not a rejection of faith. Prophets are human and can make mistakes, though they are protected from major sins.",
    "Then in the ˹veils of˺ darkness he cried out": "After Jonah boarded a ship and a storm arose, the sailors cast lots to determine who was causing the misfortune. Jonah was identified and thrown overboard, where a giant fish swallowed him. Inside the fish, in the darkness of the night, the sea, and the belly of the whale—layers upon layers of darkness—Jonah called out to Allah.",
    "\"There is no god ˹worthy of worship˺ except You": "Even in his desperate situation, Jonah's first words were a declaration of monotheism (tawheed). He affirmed Allah's sole right to worship. This is the foundation of faith and the key to salvation.",
    "Glory be to You!": "He glorified Allah, declaring Him free from any fault or injustice. Jonah acknowledged that his situation was a consequence of his own choices, not any unfairness from Allah. This is true submission—accepting responsibility and exalting Allah even when suffering.",
    "I have certainly done wrong\"": "Jonah openly confessed his mistake. He admitted he was among the wrongdoers (zalimeen) for leaving his people without permission. This sincere acknowledgment of fault, combined with his declaration of faith and glorification of Allah, formed a powerful supplication that has become known as 'the du'a of Yunus.' The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) said that whoever makes this supplication in distress will be relieved."
  },
  88: {
    "So We answered his prayer and rescued him from anguish": "Allah accepted Jonah's repentance and commanded the whale to expel him onto the shore. He emerged weak and ill, but Allah caused a plant to grow and provide him shade and nourishment until he recovered. His prayer from the depths of darkness was heard and answered. No situation is too hopeless for Allah's mercy to reach.",
    "And so do We save the ˹true˺ believers": "This is a universal promise extending beyond Jonah to all believers. Allah saves the faithful from their distress when they turn to Him sincerely. The same formula that saved Jonah—tawheed, glorification, and sincere repentance—is available to every believer. This verse gives hope that no matter how deep we have fallen, sincere return to Allah brings rescue."
  },
  89: {
    "And ˹remember˺ when Zachariah cried out to his Lord": "Zachariah was an elderly prophet who served in the temple in Jerusalem. He longed for a child to continue his work and carry on his legacy of faith. Despite his old age and his wife's barrenness, he did not give up hope in Allah's power.",
    "\"My Lord! Do not leave me childless": "Zachariah expressed his deep desire for a child. He did not want to die without an heir who would continue his mission of guiding people to Allah. This prayer was not motivated by worldly concerns but by a desire for the continuation of religious leadership.",
    "though You are the Best of Successors\"": "Even while asking for a child, Zachariah acknowledged that Allah is the ultimate inheritor of everything. If Allah chose not to give him a child, Allah Himself would take care of everything after Zachariah's death. This shows perfect etiquette in du'a—asking while accepting that Allah's decision is always best."
  },
  90: {
    "So We answered his prayer, granted him John": "Allah responded to Zachariah's prayer by blessing him with a son named John (Yahya). This was a miraculous birth—Zachariah was extremely old and his wife had been barren her entire life. But nothing is impossible for Allah. John would grow up to be a noble prophet who confirmed and supported Jesus.",
    "and made his wife fertile": "Allah 'fixed' or cured his wife's condition, enabling her to conceive and bear a child despite her previous barrenness and old age. This detail emphasizes the miraculous nature of the birth and Allah's power over all natural limitations.",
    "Indeed, they used to race in doing good": "Allah explains why this family deserved such blessings. Zachariah, his wife, and eventually John were all people who competed in performing good deeds. They did not procrastinate or do the minimum—they rushed to do good, always seeking more opportunities for righteous action.",
    "and call upon Us with hope and fear": "Their supplications were balanced—they prayed with hope (raghab) in Allah's mercy and reward, and with fear (rahab) of His displeasure and punishment. This balance prevents both arrogant presumption of Paradise and despairing of Allah's mercy. The believer hopes for the best while taking the possibility of failure seriously.",
    "totally humbling themselves before Us": "They were characterized by khushu' (humility and reverence) in their worship. Their hearts were soft, their devotion sincere, and their submission complete. This humility before Allah is the essence of true worship and the quality that draws Allah's special favor."
  },
  91: {
    "And ˹remember˺ the one who guarded her chastity": "Allah refers to Mary (Maryam) by her defining quality—her purity and chastity. She protected herself from any improper conduct, devoting herself entirely to worship in the temple. Her honor and reputation were impeccable, which made the accusation against her when she became pregnant especially painful. Yet Allah vindicates her in the Quran for all time.",
    "so We breathed into her through Our angel, ˹Gabriel,˺": "Allah sent the angel Gabriel (Jibreel) to Mary in human form. He announced that she would have a son, and by Allah's command, he breathed into her (or into her garment, according to some narrations), causing her to conceive. This was a miraculous conception without a father—a demonstration of Allah's power to create as He wills. Jesus was created by Allah's word 'Be' (kun), just as Adam was created without parents.",
    "making her and her son a sign for all peoples": "Mary and Jesus together constitute a sign (ayah) for all humanity. The miraculous virgin birth demonstrates Allah's power over normal means of reproduction. Jesus's life, miracles, and message further testified to Allah's truth. This sign is for all peoples (aalameen)—not just the Children of Israel but all of humanity throughout time. Mary is the only woman mentioned by name in the Quran, and she is honored as one of the best women ever created."
  },
  92: {
    "˹O prophets!˺ Indeed, this religion of yours is ˹only˺ one": "After mentioning numerous prophets—Noah, Abraham, David, Solomon, Job, Jonah, Zachariah, Jesus, and others—Allah declares that they all belonged to one unified religion (ummah). Despite differences in laws and practices across time, the core message was identical: believe in One God, follow His guidance, and do righteous deeds. Islam did not begin with Muhammad; it is the same essential faith of all prophets.",
    "and I am your Lord, so worship Me ˹alone˺": "The command is clear and universal: worship Allah alone. This is the common thread uniting all prophets and their true followers. Whether it was Noah calling his people, Abraham smashing idols, Moses confronting Pharaoh, or Jesus teaching his disciples, the message was always monotheism and exclusive worship of Allah."
  },
  93: {
    "Yet the people have divided it into sects": "Despite receiving one unified message, people divided themselves into competing factions and sects. They differed over what the prophets taught, added innovations, and created divisions based on tribal, national, or personal interests. Jews, Christians, and various other groups all claimed exclusive truth while deviating from the original message.",
    "But to Us they will all return": "Regardless of their divisions and claims, all people will return to Allah for judgment. He will settle their disputes and reveal who was truly on the right path. This return is inevitable, and the divisions created in this world will be meaningless before Allah's perfect judgment."
  },
  94: {
    "So whoever does good and is a believer": "The formula for success is clear: combine righteous deeds with true faith. Good deeds without faith are not accepted, and faith without good deeds is incomplete. Both components are necessary for salvation.",
    "will never be denied ˹the reward for˺ their striving": "Allah promises that no effort of the believer will be wasted or ignored. Every good deed, no matter how small, will be acknowledged and rewarded. The Arabic 'kufran' means denial or ingratitude—Allah will not be ungrateful for our efforts.",
    "for We are recording it all": "Allah is documenting every deed. Angels record all actions, and nothing escapes Allah's knowledge. This recording serves as evidence for the Day of Judgment and ensures perfect justice. It also motivates believers to persist in good deeds, knowing that everything counts."
  },
  95: {
    "It is impossible for a society which We have destroyed to ever rise again": "Once Allah destroys a nation for their disbelief and corruption, they have no second chance. The decree is final—they will not return to worldly life to make amends. The civilizations of Ad, Thamud, the people of Noah, and others were permanently ended. This serves as a warning to take the opportunity of life seriously before it is taken away."
  },
  96: {
    "until ˹after˺ Gog and Magog have broken loose ˹from the barrier˺": "Gog and Magog (Ya'juj and Ma'juj) are two groups of people who were contained behind a barrier built by Dhul-Qarnayn (mentioned in Surah Al-Kahf). Near the end of times, they will break through this barrier as one of the major signs of the Hour. Their emergence signals that the Day of Judgment is imminent.",
    "swarming down from every hill": "When released, Gog and Magog will pour forth in massive numbers, descending rapidly from every elevated place. Their sheer numbers and speed will be overwhelming. This will cause great tribulation on earth before the final Day."
  },
  97: {
    "ushering in the True Promise": "The emergence of Gog and Magog brings the 'True Promise' (al-wa'd al-haqq)—the Day of Judgment—ever closer. It is called 'true' because Allah's promise is certain and unfailing, unlike human promises that may be broken.",
    "Then—behold!—the disbelievers will stare ˹in horror, crying,˺": "When the Hour arrives, the disbelievers will be frozen in shock, their eyes fixed and unblinking in terror. The reality they denied will be undeniable, and their horror will be complete.",
    "\"Oh, woe to us! We have truly been heedless of this": "They will cry out in regret, admitting they were oblivious to this Day despite the warnings. Their heedlessness was willful—they chose to ignore the signs and reminders.",
    "In fact, we have been wrongdoers\"": "They will confess their wrongdoing, but this confession comes too late. The time for repentance and reform has passed. This self-indictment at the moment of punishment is a recurring theme—people will acknowledge their error when accountability arrives, but such acknowledgment no longer benefits them."
  },
  98: {
    "Certainly you ˹disbelievers˺ and whatever you worship instead of Allah will be the fuel of Hell": "Both the idol worshippers and their idols will be thrown into Hell together. The idols—whether statues, objects, or false deities—will share the fate of their worshippers. This is the ultimate humiliation: the gods they hoped would intercede for them become their companions in punishment.",
    "You are ˹all˺ bound to enter it": "Entry into Hell is certain for persistent disbelievers. This is not a threat to scare but a statement of fact. Those who reject Allah's guidance despite clear evidence have chosen their destination."
  },
  99: {
    "Had those idols been ˹true˺ gods, they would not have entered it": "If these objects or beings were truly divine, they would not be in Hell. Their presence in Hell proves they were never gods. A true god would have power to save himself at minimum. This logical argument exposes the absurdity of worshipping created things.",
    "And they will be there forever": "Both the worshippers and the worshipped will remain in Hell eternally. There is no exit, no parole, no end to the punishment for those who persisted in shirk (associating partners with Allah) until death."
  },
  100: {
    "In it they will groan": "The inhabitants of Hell will make groaning, moaning sounds from the intensity of their suffering. The Arabic 'zafeer' describes a deep, agonized exhale—the sound of extreme distress. This is not the groaning of complaint but of overwhelming pain.",
    "and will not be able to hear": "They will be unable to hear anything pleasant or comforting. Some scholars say this means they cannot hear each other's groaning due to the chaos. Others say they cannot hear anything beneficial like words of relief. Still others say they will be deaf to all sound except their own suffering. In any case, the torment includes isolation and deprivation of senses, adding to the punishment."
  },
  101: {
    "Surely those for whom We have destined the finest reward": "After describing the horrors of Hell, Allah now contrasts it with the fate of the righteous. Those for whom Allah has decreed 'al-husna' (the finest reward, Paradise) will have a completely different experience. This includes the prophets, the martyrs, the truthful, and all sincere believers. Allah's prior decree of good for them is based on His knowledge of their faith and righteous deeds.",
    "will be kept far away from Hell": "These blessed individuals will be removed far from Hell—not just saved from entering it, but kept at a distance from it entirely. They will not see it, smell it, or experience any of its horrors. This distancing is itself a mercy and a reward."
  },
  102: {
    "not even hearing the slightest hissing from it": "The people of Paradise will not hear even the faintest sound of Hell—not its roaring, crackling, or the cries of its inhabitants. Their tranquility will be complete and undisturbed. This contrasts with the previous verse about the people of Hell who cannot hear anything pleasant; the people of Paradise will not hear anything distressing.",
    "And they will delight forever in what their souls desire": "In Paradise, every desire will be fulfilled. Whatever their hearts wish for—whether food, drink, companionship, scenery, or pleasures we cannot imagine—will be provided. And this bliss is eternal (khalidoon)—it never ends, never diminishes, and never becomes boring. The pleasures of this world always fade, but the pleasures of Paradise are forever fresh and satisfying."
  },
  103: {
    "The Supreme Horror ˹of that Day˺ will not disturb them": "The Day of Judgment will feature terrifying events—the earth shaking, the mountains crumbling, the sun darkened, and people fleeing in panic. This is called 'al-faza' al-akbar' (the Supreme Horror). But the righteous will be protected from this terror. While others panic, they will be at peace, secure in Allah's protection. Some narrations indicate that the believers will be shaded and comforted while others suffer the terrors of that Day.",
    "and the angels will greet them, ˹saying,˺ \"This is your Day, which you have been promised\"": "Instead of facing horror, the righteous will be welcomed by angels with congratulations. The angels will announce that this is the Day they were promised—the Day of reward for their patience and faith. Imagine the joy of hearing this greeting after years of striving, sacrifice, and worship. All the hardships of worldly life become worthwhile in this moment of angelic welcome."
  },
  104: {
    "On that Day We will roll up the heavens like a scroll of writings": "Allah describes the immense power He will display on the Day of Judgment. The vast heavens—with all their stars, galaxies, and cosmic structures—will be rolled up as easily as one rolls up a piece of paper. This imagery conveys both the ease with which Allah handles creation and the total transformation that will occur. Nothing of the current universe will remain as it was.",
    "Just as We produced the first creation, ˹so˺ shall We reproduce it": "Allah presents a logical argument for resurrection: if He created everything from nothing the first time, recreating it is even easier. The One who originated life has full power to restore it. Those who doubt resurrection should consider their own existence—they were nothing, then Allah brought them into being. Restoring them after death is simpler than the original creation.",
    "That is a promise binding on Us": "Allah has promised resurrection and judgment, and His promise is absolutely binding. Unlike humans who may break promises due to inability or dishonesty, Allah always fulfills His word. This is not just a possibility but a certainty—a divine commitment.",
    "We truly uphold ˹Our promises˺!": "Allah emphasizes His track record of fulfilling promises. Every promise made to previous nations was kept—rewards for the righteous, punishment for the wicked, support for the prophets. The promise of the Day of Judgment will be fulfilled just as certainly."
  },
  105: {
    "Surely, following the ˹heavenly˺ Record, We decreed in the Scriptures": "After the 'Dhikr' (which some scholars say refers to the Preserved Tablet or the Torah), Allah decreed in the 'Zabur' (Psalms given to David) a consistent message. This shows continuity between revelations—the same truths were revealed across scriptures.",
    "\"My righteous servants shall inherit the land\"": "This decree promises that ultimately, the righteous will prevail and inherit the earth. This can refer to inheriting Paradise (called 'the land' or 'the earth' of the Hereafter), or to the eventual victory of truth over falsehood in this world, or both. The promise found in Psalm 37:29 similarly states that the righteous will inherit the land. This cross-scriptural confirmation shows the unity of Allah's message and gives believers hope that despite temporary setbacks, ultimate victory belongs to the faithful."
  },
  106: {
    "Surely this ˹Quran˺ is sufficient ˹as a reminder˺ for those devoted to worship": "Allah declares that the Quran contains everything needed for guidance. For those who are devoted to worshipping Allah (qawm 'abideen), the Quran provides complete direction. They do not need additional miracles or signs—the Quran itself is sufficient. This verse identifies the target audience of the Quran's message: those who sincerely seek to worship Allah will find it fully satisfying. Those who reject it do so not because the Quran is deficient but because they lack sincerity."
  },
  107: {
    "We have sent you ˹O Prophet˺ only as a mercy for the whole world": "This is one of the most important verses describing the Prophet Muhammad's mission. He was sent as 'rahmatan lil-'alameen'—a mercy to all the worlds. Not just to Arabs, not just to Muslims, but to all of humanity, jinn, and creation. His teachings bring mercy by guiding people away from Hell to Paradise, from ignorance to knowledge, from injustice to justice, from chaos to peace. Even non-Muslims benefit from the justice, ethics, and civilizational values Islam brought. The Prophet himself said, 'I was not sent to curse people but as a mercy.' His entire life exemplified compassion, forgiveness, and concern for others' welfare."
  },
  108: {
    "Say, \"What has been revealed to me is this: 'Your God is only One God.'": "The Prophet is commanded to summarize his core message: there is only One God worthy of worship. This is the essence of all prophetic teaching from Adam to Muhammad. Despite the Quran's many topics—law, history, ethics, afterlife—this central message of monotheism (tawheed) is the foundation of everything else.",
    "Will you then submit?\"": "After stating the truth clearly, the Prophet asks them to respond: will you submit to this truth and become Muslims (those who submit to Allah)? The choice is theirs. The evidence has been presented, the message is clear, and now the decision rests with each individual. 'Islam' literally means submission, and the question asks whether they will submit to the One True God."
  },
  109: {
    "If they turn away, then say, \"I have warned you all equally": "If they reject the message, the Prophet has fulfilled his duty. He has warned everyone equally and fairly—no one can claim they were not informed. The Prophet's responsibility was to convey the message clearly (balagh), not to force acceptance. He has done his part; they are responsible for their choice.",
    "I do not know if what you are threatened with is near or far": "The Prophet honestly admits he does not know the exact timing of the punishment or the Day of Judgment. This knowledge belongs only to Allah. The threat is real and certain, but its timing is unknown. This honest admission enhances the Prophet's credibility—he only claims knowledge of what has been revealed to him."
  },
  110: {
    "Allah surely knows what you say openly": "Allah is fully aware of every public statement—the mockery, the accusations, the rejection spoken aloud. Nothing escapes His hearing.",
    "and whatever you hide": "More significantly, Allah also knows what they conceal in their hearts—their secret doubts, their private recognition of truth, their hidden plots against the Prophet. Some may have known the truth but hid it out of pride or worldly interests. Allah knows everything, and all will be accounted for."
  },
  111: {
    "I do not know if this ˹delay˺ is possibly a test for you": "The Prophet acknowledges another possibility: perhaps the delay in punishment is itself a test. Allah may be giving them time to see if they will repent or if they will become more arrogant in their disbelief. Time is not always a blessing—it can be a test that exposes one's true character.",
    "and an enjoyment for a while": "Or perhaps the delay allows them to enjoy worldly life for a limited period before facing consequences. This enjoyment is temporary (ila heen—until a fixed time), and when it ends, accountability begins. The delay should not be mistaken for approval or escape from consequences."
  },
  112: {
    "˹In the end,˺ the Prophet said, \"My Lord! Judge ˹between us˺ in truth": "The Prophet turns to Allah, asking Him to judge between the believers and disbelievers with truth and justice. This is not a request for premature punishment but an appeal to the ultimate Judge. The Prophet leaves the matter to Allah, trusting in His perfect justice. This teaches believers to ultimately rely on Allah's judgment rather than taking matters into their own hands.",
    "And our Lord is the Most Compassionate": "Even while asking for judgment, the Prophet invokes Allah's mercy (Ar-Rahman). This balance between justice and mercy is characteristic of Islamic teaching. Allah is just but also infinitely merciful. The believers hope for His mercy while the wrongdoers should fear His justice.",
    "Whose help is sought against what you claim": "The Prophet seeks Allah's help against the false claims the disbelievers make—their accusations that the Quran is fabricated, that Muhammad is a poet or madman, that their idols have power. Allah's help is sufficient against all falsehood. This final statement of the surah is a prayer and a declaration of reliance on Allah. No matter what the enemies say or do, the believers have Allah on their side, and that is enough."
  }
};